Project Description¶

The goal of this project is to statistically describe the types of variables and to get you familiar with the entire data preparation pipeline from preparing/cleaning/encoding the dataset.

Dataset Description¶

Title: Hepatitis Dataset

Hepatitis means inflammation of the liver. The liver is a vital organ that processes nutrients, filters the blood, and fights infections. When the liver is inflamed or damaged, its function can be affected. However, hepatitis is often caused by a virus. In the United States, the most common types of viral hepatitis are hepatitis A, hepatitis B, and hepatitis C.

DESCRIPTION OF ATTRIBUTES

  • FATIGUE : A generalised sense of exhaustion or lack of energy is referred to as fatigue.
  • MALAISE : a feeling of general unwell, frequently accompanied by exhaustion, nagging discomfort, or lack of interest in activities
  • ANOREXIA : an eating disorder that makes people preoccupied with their weight and diet.
  • LIVER BIG : An enlarged liver is one that's bigger than normal.
  • LIVER FIRM : The edge of the liver is normally thin and firm.
  • SPLEEN PALPABLE : The lymphatic system's largest organ is the spleen. Although it is a vital organ for maintaining the proper balance of physiological fluids, one may survive without it.
  • SPIDERS : A common benign vascular anomaly that can manifest as solitary or many lesions is the spider nevus, also known as the spider angioma or the vascular spider.
  • ASCITES : Ascites is an accumulation of fluid between the organs in the abdominal cavity and the tissues lining the abdomen (such as the liver, spleen, stomach).
  • VARICES : Veins enlarge under the pressure of the restricted blood flow, and the liver develops scarring.
  • BILIRUBIN : Hepatitis C patients have ups and downs in their blood bilirubin levels. Jaundice may occur when bilirubin levels are high (yellowing of the skin and eyes, darker urine, and lighter-colored bowel movements).
  • ALK PHOSPHATE : An enzyme called alkaline phosphatase, often known as alk phos, is produced in the bile ducts and liver cells. When a series of liver tests is conducted, the alk phos level is a frequent test that is frequently included.
  • SGOT : Of the two liver enzymes, AST, or aspartate aminotransferase, is one. Serum glutamic-oxaloacetic transaminase, or SGOT, is another name for it. AST seeps into the circulation as a result of damaged liver cells, which raises the blood level of AST.
  • ALBUMIN : Patients with hepatitis C who have low albumin levels may have cirrhosis (advanced liver disease). Albumin concentrations can fluctuate somewhat. Ascites, or a fluid buildup in the belly, can result from extremely low albumin levels, as can edoema symptoms in the leg (called edema).
  • PROTIME : The "prothrombin time" (PT), which is measured in seconds, is one approach to determine how long it takes blood to clot (such as 13.2 seconds). The availability of blood-clotting protein is indicated by a normal PT.

Plotting boxplots for all numeric columns to see if we have outliers. The colorful portion of the boxplots is our Interquartile range(IQR). The line that passes through the colorful portion of our boxplots is our median. Any data points that lie 1.5 times of IQR above Q3 and below Q1 are outliers. The tail from the left hand side is our lower bound(q1 - (1.5 IQR)). Moving towards the colorful region from the left we have the 25th percentile(q1) before crossing the median and then the 75th percentile(q3 which is the end of the colorful region. The tail at the right end is our upper bound(q3 + (1.5 IQR)).

Creating a function that replaces outliers. The method we would be using is the Quantile based flooring and capping method. In this technique, the outlier is capped at a certain value above the 75th percentile value or floored at a factor below the 25th percentile value and we are going to be detecting and trying to replace outliers in the the continuous variables columns.

In [14]:
def replace_outliers_IQR(x):
    q1= np.percentile(x,25)
    q3= np.percentile(x,75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    low_bound = q1 - (1.5*iqr)
    upr_bound = q3 + (1.5*iqr)
    x = np.where(x >= upr_bound, upr_bound, np.where(x <= low_bound, low_bound, x))
    return x

Density plots uses the kernel density estimation so they are also known as kernel density estimation plots. The region of the plots with a high peak is the region with maximum data points residing between the values. Below, I used the kernel density estimation to overlay the curve on the histograms of the continues variables in my data. KDE or the Kernel Density Estimation uses Gaussian Kernels to estimate the Probability Density Function of a random variable. Density plots have an advantage over Histograms because they determine the Shape of the distribution more efficiently than histograms.They do not have to depend on the number of bins used unlike in histograms.

CONCLUSION

In this work, I pre-processed the data by cleaning it taking note of missing values and outliers. I replaced all my missing values with median observation and I used the matrix method to identify high leverage points. The final part of this work was concerned with my visualization of all variables and how they affect each other. Data pre-processing and visualization is a critical task in data analysis as it can help analyst make proper predictions.
